Unfortunately, today, it has ceased to be the tone of many of the meetings and the promise of politics - kinder and kinder - was long forgotten, if it has ever been fulfilled.
It has become increasingly apparent that different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party, and that each opinion is judged on whether or not it is acceptable by party leadership.
This started a short time after Jeremy took the lead, because those colleagues with whom he thought he shared a similar political perspective began to expect me a revolution and to take positions with which he would never agree - whether they were on national security or on the single market in the EU.
Whenever I speak in public (and I don't really care what I say), there are a lot of insults on social media that appeal to the \"decommissioning\" by denouncing the policies of the center, telling me that I must not belong to the Labour Party.
And it's not just me who's going through this.
In fact, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the comments addressed to me tend to be political in nature.
I am amazed at the professionalism and determination of these colleagues who face a barrage of sexist or racist insults every day, but who never go back to them.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is the way these levels of insult have become normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we no longer be inclusive, and with each motion of “censorship” or change of the rules of selection the party narrows its views.
I have received numerous advice over the last two years urging me to keep my head down, not to be so expressive, and that would - it would be all right - for me.
But that's not why I came to make politics.
Since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student, driven by the negligence of Thatcher's government that left the classroom of my school literally comprehensive in rubble, I tried to fight for better public services for those they need most, either as a coach or as a minister in the government.
I've never hidden my policies, including the last elections.
No one in Nottingham East could have become somehow confused about my political positions and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
For those who promoted the motion on Friday, all I have to say is that when the country heads for a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on the issue of my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in fact, the message I have is not for the Momentum of Nottingham; it is for my constituents, members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threats of \"dejection\" or political files will prevent me from acting in the sense of what I believe to be the interests of all of you.
