John Edward: Language competences are essential for global citizens
The independent schools of Scotland benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, with this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30 000 students spread throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service for both students and parents.
Independent schools intend to prepare their students for further study and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought-after subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If we talk to a man in a language he understands, we can get into his mind.
If we talk to him in his own language, we can get into his heart.
This quote reminds us that we cannot only rely on English when we want to create relations and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of recent exams this year, we found that languages are at the top of the table, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum classification of A.
This data, collected from the 74 schools at the height of the SCIS, showed that 72% of the students obtained the maximum A score in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that the Scottish independent schools are favoring foreign languages as vital competences that will unquestionably serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
A survey by the United Kingdom Employment and Competences Commission in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons for the difficulty of employers in filling vacancies, 17% concerned the lack of language skills.
Knowing other languages is therefore increasingly an imperative for preparing the younger generation for their future careers.
With more potential employment opportunities requiring knowledge of languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if they have learned a second language, they will have a tangible advantage in the future with a life skills like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to keep a conversation, the French being the only language spoken by a two-digit ratio, 15%.
Therefore, investing now in language teaching is important for today's children.
The field of various languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children with a better chance of finding employment with relevance.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the United Kingdom for the 2020 horizon, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose from in-house schools, supported by specialized teaching staff in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a teaching environment that prepares children and gives them the necessary skills for success, whatever the future holds for them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance to the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be regarded as ‘international communication skills’.
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence for young Scots.
You have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
