The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dorm where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, shoes and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to collect to bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
We know it won't change the students' behavior instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, as we all have the right to know the health effects of smoking option - added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in - making direct - still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students make this a growing problem.
