Here are some key facts about Palu and Donggala on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of the province of Sulawesi Central, located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 inhabitants in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a region that extends over 300 km of coastline in the northwest of the island of Sulawesi.
The region, with an administrative status lower than that of a province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the main economic activities of Sulawesi Central Province, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel extraction is also important in the province, but concentrates mostly on Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the last 100 years, according to the Indonesian disaster management agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also hit the western part of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Seismic Fire Ring, being regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the main earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: On December 26, a strong earthquake on the western coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, in northern Sumatra, resulted in a tsunami that reached 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra at the end of March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on Nias Island off Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake hit southern Java, the most populous island in Indonesia, resulting in a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing almost 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake hit the city of Padang, capital of the western Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake hit one of the Mentawai islands off Sumatra, unleashing a tsunami with waves up to 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake hit the Pidie Jaya region in Aceh, spreading destruction and panic among people who remembered the devastation caused by the deadly earthquake and tsunami of 2004.
This time there was no tsunami, but more than 100 people died underground under the rubble of the buildings.
2018: Great earthquakes hit the Indonesian island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the northern side of the island.
The earthquakes destroyed thousands of buildings, leaving thousands of tourists temporarily isolated.
