Updated information about Red Sea: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there was a decrease in concentrations of Red Sea in some areas of Tampa Bay.
FWC reported that conditions of less proliferation of stains were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The stain of the Red Sea extends about 201 km along the coast, from the county of Pinellas to the north to the county of Lee to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less areas than last week.
The Red Sea was also spotted in Pasco County.
Last week, there were average concentrations along or off the coast of Pinella County, low concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, high-bottom concentrations in Manatee County, high-bottom concentrations along or off the coast of Sarasota County, medium-to-middle concentrations in Charlotte County, high-bottom concentrations along or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritations in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritations in the northwestern part of Florida.
